# 3. Model(s) Building (continued)
##### After having built the clusters that model the customer-product relationship based on behaviour in relation to price changes, I want to be able to extract business rules that characterize cluster membership. The main objective is to be able to use the previousy built customer-product relationship clusters via business rules as part of other processes and workflows. I will be a using a decision tree classification model, as it is one of the easiest models to interpret. Also, the rule-based structure of the model makes it possible to export and reuse in other applications. As previously, I will be building two classification models: one model corresponding to the clusters based on absolute values, and one model corresponding to the clusters based on percentages.

%md
##### Next, I create the model using the input table and the settings table created previously.

paragraphs.title: create MODEL for CLASSIFICATION, #1
paragraphs.text:
%script

begin

dbms_data_mining.CREATE_MODEL(
    model_name          => 'OML_CLASSIFICATION_MOD_WA1',
    mining_function     => dbms_data_mining.classification,
    data_table_name     => 'OML_CLASSES_WA1',
    case_id_column_name => 'ID',
    target_column_name  => 'CLASS',
    settings_table_name => 'OML_CLASSIFICATION_SET_WA1'
    );

end;

paragraphs.text:
%md
##### In order to extract the business rules, I need to parse the PMML format. Consequently, I am creating a results table that holds the rules extracted from the PMML format.

paragraphs.title: create RESULTS for CLASSIFICATION, #1
paragraphs.text:
%script

create table OML_CLASSIFICATION_RES_WA1
    as select
        "NODE" as "NODE",
        case
            when "RULE2" like '%DIF%' then
                "RULE1"||' and '||"RULE2" 
            else "RULE1"
            end as "RULE",
        "CLUSTER" as "CLUSTER",
        "COUNT" as "COUNT"
    from (
        select
            n_id as "NODE",
            case 
                when sp_field like '%DIF%' then 
                    replace(replace(sp_field||' '||sp_operator||' '||
                    to_char(cast(sp_value as number(6,2)),'90.99'),'lessOrEqual','<='),'greaterThan','>') 
                else replace(replace(cp_field1||' '||cp_operator1||' '||
                    to_char(cast(cp_value1 as number(6,2)),'90.99'),'lessOrEqual','<='),'greaterThan','>') 
                end as "RULE1",
            replace(replace(cp_field2||' '||cp_operator2||' '||
                to_char(cast(cp_value2 as number(6,2)),'90.99'),'lessOrEqual','<='),'greaterThan','>') 
                as "RULE2",
            t_value as "CLUSTER",
            t_count as "COUNT"
        from (
            select
                *
            from
                XMLTable('for $s in /PMML/TreeModel//ScoreDistribution
                    return
                        <scores 
                        nid="{$s/../@id}"
                        spfield="{$s/../SimplePredicate/@field}"
                        spoperator="{$s/../SimplePredicate/@operator}"
                        spvalue="{$s/../SimplePredicate/@value}"
                        cpfield1="{$s/../CompoundPredicate/SimplePredicate[1]/@field}"
                        cpoperator1="{$s/../CompoundPredicate/SimplePredicate[1]/@operator}"
                        cpvalue1="{$s/../CompoundPredicate/SimplePredicate[1]/@value}"
                        cpfield2="{$s/../CompoundPredicate/SimplePredicate[2]/@field}"
                        cpoperator2="{$s/../CompoundPredicate/SimplePredicate[2]/@operator}"
                        cpvalue2="{$s/../CompoundPredicate/SimplePredicate[2]/@value}"
                        sdvalue="{$s/@value}"
                        sdcount="{$s/@recordCount}"
                        />'
            passing dbms_data_mining.GET_MODEL_DETAILS_XML('OML_CLASSIFICATION_MOD_WA1')
            columns
                n_id number path '/scores/@nid',
                sp_field varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@spfield',
                sp_operator varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@spoperator',
                sp_value varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@spvalue',
                cp_field1 varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@cpfield1',
                cp_operator1 varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@cpoperator1',
                cp_value1 varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@cpvalue1',
                cp_field2 varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@cpfield2',
                cp_operator2 varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@cpoperator2',
                cp_value2 varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@cpvalue2',
                t_value varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@sdvalue',
                t_count number path '/scores/@sdcount')
            order by
                n_id, t_value
            ) s2
        ) s1
    order by
        "NODE", "CLUSTER";

paragraphs.text:
%md
##### I check the resulting rules. Initially, I see all the rules corresponding to the splits for all nodes and clusters in the decision tree. This view corresponds to the full probability distribution of clusters at each node’s level. For a clearer picture, I aggregate at node level, and only pick the most important cluster from the probability distribution. This rule format can be embedded in other applications and makes it easy to explain cluster membership for speciffic customer-product relationships.

paragraphs.title: view RESULTS for CLASSIFICATION, #1
paragraphs.text:
%sql

select
    *
from
    OML_CLASSIFICATION_RES_WA1;

3.2.2. Classification CUSTOMER and PRODUCT GROUP by DIFFERENCE TO AVERAGE PRICE(S) PERCENTAGE

The second classification model creates the customer-product relationship decision tree corresponding to the average price(s) differences as percentages clustering model. After creating the model, I will be extracting the rules, in order to make them reusable in other processes or workflows.

paragraphs.text:
%md
##### I start by creating the input dataset for this case. I am using a new identifier for my customer-product relationship, created by concatenating the Customer and Product Group columns.

paragraphs.title: create CLASSES, work, #2
paragraphs.text:
%script

create table OML_CLASSES_WA2
    as select
        "ID" as "ID",
        "DIFP LAST1M" as "DIFP LAST1M",
        "DIFP LAST6M" as "DIFP LAST6M",
        "DIFP TODATE" as "DIFP TODATE",
        "CLUSTER" as "CLUSTER"
    from
        OML_CLUSTERING_RES_WA2;

msg.data:
Table OML_CLASSES_WA2 created.


---------------------------

paragraphs.title: , drop

msg.data:
Table OML_CLASSES_WA2 dropped.

%md
##### In order to extract the business rules, I need to parse the PMML format. Consequently, I am creating a results table that holds the rules extracted from the PMML format.

paragraphs.title: create RESULTS for CLASSIFICATION, #2
paragraphs.text:
%script

create table OML_CLASSIFICATION_RES_WA2
as select
        "NODE" as "NODE",
        case
            when "RULE2" like '%DIF%' then
                "RULE1"||' and '||"RULE2" 
            else "RULE1"
            end as "RULE",
        "CLUSTER" as "CLUSTER",
        "COUNT" as "COUNT"
    from (
        select
            n_id as "NODE",
            case 
                when sp_field like '%DIF%' then 
                    replace(replace(sp_field||' '||sp_operator||' '||
                    to_char(cast(sp_value as number(6,2)),'90.99'),'lessOrEqual','<='),'greaterThan','>') 
                else replace(replace(cp_field1||' '||cp_operator1||' '||
                    to_char(cast(cp_value1 as number(6,2)),'90.99'),'lessOrEqual','<='),'greaterThan','>') 
                end as "RULE1",
            replace(replace(cp_field2||' '||cp_operator2||' '||
                to_char(cast(cp_value2 as number(6,2)),'90.99'),'lessOrEqual','<='),'greaterThan','>') 
                as "RULE2",
            t_value as "CLUSTER",
            t_count as "COUNT"
        from (
            select
                *
            from
                XMLTable('for $s in /PMML/TreeModel//ScoreDistribution
                    return
                        <scores 
                        nid="{$s/../@id}"
                        spfield="{$s/../SimplePredicate/@field}"
                        spoperator="{$s/../SimplePredicate/@operator}"
                        spvalue="{$s/../SimplePredicate/@value}"
                        cpfield1="{$s/../CompoundPredicate/SimplePredicate[1]/@field}"
                        cpoperator1="{$s/../CompoundPredicate/SimplePredicate[1]/@operator}"
                        cpvalue1="{$s/../CompoundPredicate/SimplePredicate[1]/@value}"
                        cpfield2="{$s/../CompoundPredicate/SimplePredicate[2]/@field}"
                        cpoperator2="{$s/../CompoundPredicate/SimplePredicate[2]/@operator}"
                        cpvalue2="{$s/../CompoundPredicate/SimplePredicate[2]/@value}"
                        sdvalue="{$s/@value}"
                        sdcount="{$s/@recordCount}"
                        />'
            passing dbms_data_mining.GET_MODEL_DETAILS_XML('OML_CLASSIFICATION_MOD_WA2')
            columns
                n_id number path '/scores/@nid',
                sp_field varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@spfield',
                sp_operator varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@spoperator',
                sp_value varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@spvalue',
                cp_field1 varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@cpfield1',
                cp_operator1 varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@cpoperator1',
                cp_value1 varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@cpvalue1',
                cp_field2 varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@cpfield2',
                cp_operator2 varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@cpoperator2',
                cp_value2 varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@cpvalue2',
                t_value varchar2(1000) path '/scores/@sdvalue',
                t_count number path '/scores/@sdcount')
            order by
                n_id, t_value
            ) s2
        ) s1
    order by
        "NODE", "CLUSTER";

paragraphs.text:
%md
##### I check the resulting rules. Initially, I see all the rules corresponding to the splits for all nodes and clusters in the decision tree. This view corresponds to the full probability distribution of clusters at each node’s level. For a clearer picture, I aggregate at node level, and only pick the most important cluster from the probability distribution. This rule format can be embedded in other applications and makes it easy to explain cluster membership for speciffic customer-product relationships.

msg.data:
3.2.3. Classification CUSTOMER and PRODUCT GROUP business insight(s)

To have a better view of the type of business insights I can get from the classification results, I use the same examples I had previously showcased for the clustering step. In addition to the characteristics of the customer-product relationship clusters insights, I now also have a set of business rules that can adequately explain and classify said membership.

paragraphs.text:
%md
##### My first example for the #1 model type is a customer-product cluster that models a relationship which is responsive to price decrease, mostly long term. The cluster is characterized by being slightly variant on short term price decrease, slightly variant on medium term price decrease and moderately variant on long term price decrease. What this means is, if the price for the product groups in question changes in accordance to cluster characteristics, there is a likelyhood that the identified customers will buy. Additionally, I now have the business rules that can describe customer-price relationship’s membership to the cluster.
##### My second example for the #1 model type is a customer-product cluster that models a relationship which is responsive to price decrease, mostly short term. The cluster is characterized by being highly variant on short term price decrease, moderately variant on medium term price decrease and slightly variant on long term price decrease. What this means is, if the price for the product groups in question changes in accordance to cluster characteristics, there is a likelyhood that the identified customers will buy. Additionally, I now have the business rules that can describe customer-price relationship’s membership to the cluster.

### 3.3. Forecast CUSTOMER and PRODUCT GROUP by DIFFERENCE TO AVERAGE PRICE(S)
##### Now that I have both the customer-product relationship clusters and the rules behind them, what I want to do next is get an idea of how will the transactions evolve in the future for various clusters. To achieve that, I will be using a forecasting model. Specifically, I will be applying a variation of the Holt-Winters triple exponential smoothing model to forecast transactions for the next 6 months interval. As previously, I will be applying two exponential smoothing models: one model corresponding to the clusters based on absolute values, and one model corresponding to the clusters based on percentages.

Now that I have both the customer-product relationship clusters and the rules behind them, what I want to do next is get an idea of how will the transactions evolve in the future for various clusters. To achieve that, I will be using a forecasting model. Specifically, I will be applying a variation of the Holt-Winters triple exponential smoothing model to forecast transactions for the next 6 months interval. As previously, I will be applying two exponential smoothing models: one model corresponding to the clusters based on absolute values, and one model corresponding to the clusters based on percentages.

paragraphs.text:
%md
##### I start by creating the input dataset. I do that by merging the intial transactions table with the clustering results for each of transactions. Because my forecast will be done at month level, I am also adding a month column to be used as time dimension for the time series. As I have two types of clustering models, each of the transactions will have two clusters associated, one for the clustering based on average price(s) differences as absolute values, and one for the clustering based on average price(s) differences as percentages.

paragraphs.title: create TRANSACTIONS, work, clusters
paragraphs.text:
%script

create table OML_TRANSACTIONS_WC
    as select
        substr(OML_TRANSACTIONS."DATE",7,4)||substr(OML_TRANSACTIONS."DATE",4,2) as "MONTH",
        OML_TRANSACTIONS."CUSTOMER" as "CUSTOMER",
        OML_TRANSACTIONS."PRODUCT GROUP" as "PRODUCT GROUP",
        OML_CLUSTERING_RES_WA1."CLUSTER" as "CLUSTER #1",
        OML_CLUSTERING_RES_WA2."CLUSTER" as "CLUSTER #2",
        OML_TRANSACTIONS."UNITS" as "UNITS",
        OML_TRANSACTIONS."PRICE" as "PRICE",
        OML_TRANSACTIONS."PROFIT" as "PROFIT"
    from
        OML_TRANSACTIONS
    join
        OML_CLUSTERING_RES_WA1 on OML_TRANSACTIONS."CUSTOMER"=OML_CLUSTERING_RES_WA1."CUSTOMER" and OML_TRANSACTIONS."PRODUCT GROUP"=OML_CLUSTERING_RES_WA1."PRODUCT GROUP"
    join
        OML_CLUSTERING_RES_WA2 on OML_TRANSACTIONS."CUSTOMER"=OML_CLUSTERING_RES_WA2."CUSTOMER" and OML_TRANSACTIONS."PRODUCT GROUP"=OML_CLUSTERING_RES_WA2."PRODUCT GROUP";

### 3.3.1. Forecast CUSTOMER and PRODUCT GROUP by DIFFERENCE TO AVERAGE PRICE(S) VALUE
##### Because of the nature of time series forecasting models, I will need to create subsets for each of my cases. Also, due to focus of the analysis being the customer-product relationship, I decide on using ‘units’ as the parameter for which the forcasting will be done. As done previously, I will use the same examples I had showcased for the clustering and classification steps. I will be applying the forecasting model for each of my 2+2 examples (2 examples for clusters based on average price(s) differences as absolute values and 2 examples for clusters based on average price(s) differences as percentages).

paragraphs.title: create CUSTOMER and PRODUCT GROUP, #1, CLUSTER G, CLUSTER C, time series
paragraphs.text:
%script

create table OML_TSUNITS_WC1G
as select
        rownum as "ID",
        "UNITS" as "UNITS"
    from (
        select
            "MONTH" as "MONTH",
            max("CLUSTER #1") as "CLUSTER",
            sum("UNITS") as "UNITS",
            cast(avg("PRICE") as numeric(6,2)) as "PRICE",
            sum("PROFIT") as "PROFIT"
        from
            OML_TRANSACTIONS_WC
        where
            "CLUSTER #1"='G'
        group by
            "MONTH"
        order by
            "MONTH"
        ) s;

create table OML_TSUNITS_WC1C
as select
        rownum as "ID",
        "UNITS" as "UNITS"
    from (
        select
            "MONTH" as "MONTH",
            max("CLUSTER #1") as "CLUSTER",
            sum("UNITS") as "UNITS",
            cast(avg("PRICE") as numeric(6,2)) as "PRICE",
            sum("PROFIT") as "PROFIT"
        from
            OML_TRANSACTIONS_WC
        where
            "CLUSTER #1"='C'
        group by
            "MONTH"
        order by
            "MONTH"
        ) s;

paragraphs.title: create CUSTOMER and PRODUCT GROUP, #2, CLUSTER A, CLUSTER G, time series
paragraphs.text:
%script

create table OML_TSUNITS_WC2A
as select
        rownum as "ID",
        "UNITS" as "UNITS"
    from (
        select
            "MONTH" as "MONTH",
            max("CLUSTER #1") as "CLUSTER",
            sum("UNITS") as "UNITS",
            cast(avg("PRICE") as numeric(6,2)) as "PRICE",
            sum("PROFIT") as "PROFIT"
        from
            OML_TRANSACTIONS_WC
        where
            "CLUSTER #2"='A'
        group by
            "MONTH"
        order by
            "MONTH"
        ) s;

create table OML_TSUNITS_WC2G
as select
        rownum as "ID",
        "UNITS" as "UNITS"
    from (
        select
            "MONTH" as "MONTH",
            max("CLUSTER #1") as "CLUSTER",
            sum("UNITS") as "UNITS",
            cast(avg("PRICE") as numeric(6,2)) as "PRICE",
            sum("PROFIT") as "PROFIT"
        from
            OML_TRANSACTIONS_WC
        where
            "CLUSTER #2"='G'
        group by
            "MONTH"
        order by
            "MONTH"
        ) s;

msg.data:
3.3.3. Forecast CUSTOMER and PRODUCT GROUP business insight(s)

To have a better view of the type of business insights I can get from the forecasting results, I have a look at the forecasts in the context of the example cases they were built on top of. I am representing the forecasting results associated for each of the example cases, to have a view over future evolution of transacted units for speciffic customer-product relationships. In addition to the characteristics of the customer-product relationship clusters insights, I now also have the 6 months forecast.

paragraphs.text:
%md
#####My first example for the #1 model type is a customer-product cluster that models a relationship which is responsive to price decrease, mostly long term. The cluster is characterized by being slightly variant on short term price decrease, slightly variant on medium term price decrease and moderately variant on long term price decrease. What this means is, if the price for the product groups in question changes in accordance to cluster characteristics, there is a likelyhood that the identified customers will buy. Additionally, I now have the forecast for the next 6 months.
##### My second example for the #1 model type is a customer-product cluster that models a relationship which is responsive to price decrease, mostly short term. The cluster is characterized by being highly variant on short term price decrease, moderately variant on medium term price decrease and slightly variant on long term price decrease. What this means is, if the price for the product groups in question changes in accordance to cluster characteristics, there is a likelyhood that the identified customers will buy. Additionally, I now have the forecast for the next 6 months.
